  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Expositor's Greek Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Luke 1:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Indicates the practical aim: to give certainty in regard to matters of Christian belief.—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "περὶ ὧν κ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "λόγων",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ": an attraction, to be thus resolved: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "περὶ τῶν λόγων οὓς κατηχήθης",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "λόγων",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " is best taken = matters (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "πραγμάτων",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Luke 1:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), histories (Weizsäcker), not doctrines. Doubtless this is a Hebraistic sense, but that is no objection, for after all Lk. is a Hellenist and no pure Greek, and even in this preface, whose pure Greek has been so often praised, he is a Hellenist to a large extent. (So Hahn, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Einleitung",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", p. 6.) The subject of instruction for young Christians in those early years was the teaching, the acts, and the experience of Jesus: their “catechism” historic not doctrinal.—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "κατηχήθης",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ": is this word used here in a technical sense = formally and systematically instructed, or in the general sense of “have been informed more or less correctly”? (So Kypke.) The former is more probable. The verb (from ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "κατὰ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἠχέω",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") is mainly Hellenistic in usage, rare in profane authors, not found in O. T. The N. T. usage, confined to Lk. and Paul, points to regular instruction (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
